VOICE/TONE RECOMMENDATION
================================================================================

recommended_voice:   Confident beauty editor with a warm, editorial authority

tone_characteristics:
  1. Aspirational but inclusive — makes high-skill looks feel achievable by framing
     simpler alternatives clearly; never condescending about beginner options
  2. Specific over vague — names exact colours (butter yellow, sage green, blush
     pink), tools (size 000 liner brush, dotting tool), and timings (20 minutes /
     90–120 minutes) so copy has texture and credibility
  3. Present-tense authority — writes as though these looks are happening now on
     real hands, not theoretically trending
  4. Restrained excitement — not hyperbolic ("OMG stunning!") but genuinely engaged;
     the kind of voice that makes you trust the curation
  5. British English throughout — spellings, phrasing, rhythm

language_style:
  Second person ("your nails," "you want"). Active verbs. Short declarative
  sentences for key statements. No em dashes. No filler words or buzzword padding.
  Avoid: "stunning," "gorgeous," "amazing," "literally," "groundbreaking" (ironic
  unless deliberately referencing the cultural shorthand). Analogies welcome for
  technique explanations.

audience_match:
  This reader is 25–38, follows beauty accounts, books regular salon appointments
  but also attempts DIY between visits. She wants to feel informed and inspired
  simultaneously — this voice treats her as an intelligent adult who can handle
  technical nuance alongside mood-board energy.

